name: Adam B. Schiff
content:
Trump‚Äôs Big Lie didn‚Äôt disappear after January 6 ‚Äì it metastasized.

In the wake of the 2020 election, states across the country have enacted a wave of voter suppression laws to make it more difficult for everyone, but in particular communities of color, to cast their votes. Texas just signed into law a provision that makes it easier to overturn an election - no actual evidence of fraud required, which follows voter suppression efforts in Georgia and other states.

That‚Äôs not all: Trump‚Äôs former National Security Advisor Michael Flynn spent his Memorial Day weekend suggesting a military coup might be in order to oust and replace President Biden, and invoking the specter of the military coup in Myanmar. And former President Trump has reportedly been telling his associates that he‚Äôll be reinstated to the presidency by August. (He won‚Äôt be.)

Make no mistake. Our democracy is at risk.

I‚Äôve long said that our democracy is not self-effectuating. It‚Äôs up to us, each of us in every generation, to uphold it and make it stronger. To expand its promise of equality and justice for all. And to protect, fortify, and defend it. We‚Äôre now at a critical juncture in the history of our democracy, and we need a whole-of-government, bipartisan effort to ensure it survives.

It‚Äôs why we need to pass H.R. 1, the For the People Act, and H.R. 4, the John Lewis Voting Rights Act, to expand and protect the right to vote, roll back decades‚Äô worth of state efforts to disenfranchise communities of color, end dark money in politics, help root out corruption, end gerrymandering and strengthen ethics laws for public officials. And it‚Äôs why I will soon introduce the Protecting Our Democracy Act, a landmark reform package that will prevent future presidential abuses, restore our system of checks and balances, strengthen accountability and transparency and protect our elections. name: Mike Johnson
content:
The tragic loss of Calvary student Lane Mangum has shaken many in the Shreveport community, and our prayers remain with his beloved family. My brother-in-law, Calvary‚Äôs Pastor John Lary, and my dear friend, Calvary Superintendent Chad McDowell, were with Lane‚Äôs dad last night and are walking through the tragedy with the tight-knit Calvary community, and all of them could use prayer at this difficult time.

I‚Äôm sharing Chad‚Äôs post here to help him communicate information to the many people who are following these events.

‚ÄúFor I am convinced that neither death nor life, nor angels nor rulers, nor things present nor things to come, nor powers, nor height nor depth, nor anything else in all creation, will be able to separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord.‚Äù
(Romans 8:38-39)

Chad McDowell is with Justin Hayley Grace and 99 others.
7 hrs ¬∑

I love you, Lane Mangum! Many pictures are being shared of this awesome guy. I wanted to add some to the collection.

Man, I love this guy right here! It doesn‚Äôt seem real. I simply don‚Äôt have the words because there really doesn‚Äôt seem to be any for this difficult time. So many of us shaking our heads, crying, and just in total shock. Lord, please wrap your arms around these families and all of us and provide us with comfort that can only come from you.

For media outlet purposes trying to reach me for comment, here you go: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt have the words to adequately express how heartbroken all of us are about this tragic accident. We are deeply saddened at the loss of Lane Mangum and as expected are in shock and having a difficult time coming to grips with the reality of what has happened. Our thoughts, prayers, love and support are with his family. We are grateful for the outpouring of love and support for our CBA family and covet the ongoing prayers for all involved.‚Äù

Arrangements of Lane‚Äôs celebration of life service will be forthcoming in the days ahead.

Please allow me to clarify a couple of things regarding a couple of gatherings that are circulating throughout social media.

Calvary Baptist Church has their regular Wednesday night student services still scheduled. They have posted to CBC Students Facebook about tonight being a Prayer Night. ‚ÄúAll of our hearts are hurting. Let‚Äôs come together, tonight @ 6:30 pm in the NexGen room.‚Äù All students are welcomed and encouraged to attend.

Tomorrow morning clarification: Calvary Football Team had a regularly scheduled workout for tomorrow morning at 8:00 am. Coach Rodney Guin was going to address the team as well as Clint Davis with Clint Davis Counseling Services. The softball and baseball teams are joining the football team tomorrow morning as a time of supporting one another and processing grief together. Coach Rodney Guin was going to make a few comments to the team and then Clint Davis‚Äô team was going to speak to the group. CBC Pastoral Staff as well as several coaches will be on hand as well.

I haven‚Äôt checked social media lately but gather from the text messages coming through there may be some confusion as to what tomorrow was scheduled to be. The arrangements on the celebration of Lane‚Äôs life service will be announced in the next couple of days. Please help spread that word.

Hope this helps! We are all hurting. We all want to do what we can to love and support these two families that were involved. Both families have continually expressed their appreciation to everyone and ask for continued prayers.

#WeAreCalvary #Grateful #WeRemainGrateful #GodIsFaithful

*Please consider sharing the post as a means of communication about tonight's service (6:30 pm NexGen Room) for ALL students and then tomorrow morning is for group of student-athletes that are teammates of Lane's.

name: Robert E. Latta
content:
Every year since 1976, the Hyde Amendment has been renewed into law on a #bipartisan basis. This is not the case with President Biden‚Äôs proposed 2022 Fiscal Budget.

The Hyde Amendment prohibits federal funding from being used to fund elective abortions. It has saved over 2.4 million lives since becoming law, and it should continue to be renewed. Nearly 60% of Americans agree that taxpayer money should not be used to fund abortions.

I have and will continue to protect those who can not protect themselves. I strongly urge President Biden to reconsider the Hyde Amendment which he supported during his time in the U.S. Senate.

name: Roger F. Wicker
content:
As the son of a World War II veteran, the father of an Air Force officer, and as a veteran myself, I understand the needs of retired service members and their families.

This year I have worked on several important bills to improve life for our veterans. My State Veterans Home Relief Act, which was enacted in March, provided $500 million to help advance veteran housing projects that had been delayed across the country. Of this money, $54 million will go toward a construction project for the State Veteran Home in Gulfport, providing quality housing for 100 veterans and creating roughly 200 nursing jobs.

I am also supporting legislation to help veterans who are disabled or affected by combat-related illness. I am currently a cosponsor of the Major Richard Star Act, which would allow disabled veterans to receive full retirement pay if their combat injuries forced them to retire early. I am also cosponsoring legislation that would improve access to VA care for those who served in proximity to burn pits and were potentially exposed to toxic fumes.

These measures enjoy bipartisan support and should be passed as soon as possible.

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: In 2020, I had a conversation with Denali Brewing Company founding partner and operator of Denali Brewpub, Sassan Mossanen, about how the COVID-19 pandemic was impacting their local business. Flash forward a year, I had a chance to meet with he and his family in Talkeetna at the brewpub for a status update. Last year they faced an unimaginable loss in revenue. Luckily, their business has come a long way since last year but they are still not able to function at full capacity. Normally Sassan has about 85 employees. This year he has around 45 and is operating on limited hours because businesses across the state are struggling to recruit a workforce to cover the demand. I‚Äôm really encouraged to see revenue starting to flow again and people excited to get out and support our local businesses, but the ripple effects of the pandemic are still presenting local business owners with significant challenges. I appreciate the Mossanens for giving me a better understanding the realities facing small Alaskan businesses.

name: Sam Graves
content:
As we approach the 77th Anniversary of D-Day, I want to share some history about the preparations that led up to the Allied invasion of Nazi-occupied Europe.

For months before the landings at Normandy, France, Allied forces worked to deceive Axis forces. Through Operation Fortitude, the Allies created phantom field armies, comprised of inflatable tanks, fake landing craft, and dummy planes.

These phantom formations, along with strategically leaked intelligence, were meant to convince the Nazis that the Allies would strike at Norway or the Pas de Calais.

These actions kept German reserves waiting for a seaborne attack at Pas de Calais even after D-Day, helping Allied forces gain a strong foothold for liberating Europe.

name: Don Young
content:
Yesterday, I stopped by Midnight Sun Brewing company to meet with the Brewers Guild of Alaska. The Brewers Guild does important work serving as the voice for its member breweries across Alaska. The COVID-19 pandemic has hit our state's breweries hard, but the Brewers Guild has played a prominent role in helping our beer producers weather the storm.

The beer industry supports 4,722 jobs in Alaska, with a total economic impact of nearly $800 million each year. We must be doing everything we can to support this crucial sector. We have turned a corner in this pandemic, and with the summer tourism ramps up, I am excited for visitors from around the world to taste Alaska's locally produced brews for themselves.

I want to thank the Brewers Guild of Alaska for a very productive conversation. I also want to thank Josh Hegna of Girdwood Brewing, Lee Ellis of Midnight Sun Brewing, and everyone who made this visit and discussion possible. If you know me, you're aware that I only drink during odd-numbered years, so that beer flight will undoubtedly be a highlight for 2021! üçªüçª

name: David P. Joyce
content:
As a former prosecutor who had the privilege of working alongside law enforcement for over two decades, I know firsthand that our police officers are often the first on the scene when someone is suffering a mental health crisis. But without adequate training, those encounters can be both dangerous and tragic.

That's why, I joined my colleagues on both sides of the aisle in introducing the Law Enforcement Training for Mental Health Crisis Response Act. By increasing coordination between law enforcement and local mental health professionals and providing officers with the training they need to respond to those in crisis, this bill will improve the safety of our communities as well as the safety of the men and women in blue sworn to protect them.

name: Garret Graves
content:
The Mid-Barataria Sediment Diversion is about coastal Louisiana‚Äôs survival ‚Äì we are on a trajectory to irreversible elimination of our fisheries, wildlife, habitats, industries, culture and coastal communities without a paradigm shift in our decisions, investments, and management of the Mississippi River System.

We need to listen to every concern raised to make sure we do this in an informed manner.

To learn more, go to coastal.la.gov

If we keep moving in this direction that prioritizes adaptation through innovation, then we can expedite the progress we need to make in restoring our wetlands and coastal areas. This is about using the Mississippi River and replicating the very process that mother nature used to create Louisiana.

A majority of coastal land loss in Louisiana is tied back to the levees that were built on the lower Mississippi River System. Dating back to the early 1900s, the state of Louisiana used to grow approximately three-quarters of a square mile per year ‚Äì our state was getting bigger. When the Corps of Engineers built levees on the river in the early 1930s, the wetlands began to starve, and our state began losing an average of 26 square miles per year. Levees prevent the river‚Äôs ability to naturally replenish the wetlands with freshwater and sediment to backfill canals, which has compounded the effects of saltwater intrusion, storm surge and other contributors to coastal land loss.

Reconnecting the river with adjacent areas to build land allows the land-building process to continue. We need to continue moving forward and making the best decision for Louisiana and our children and grandchildren.

name: Derek Kilmer
content:
One of the best parts about this job is meeting incredibly talented folks in every corner of our region. Last week that included Lara Hansen, Chief Scientist & Executive Director of EcoAdapt - a nonprofit based out of Bainbridge Island that aims to meet the challenges of global climate change through adaptation research, training, and knowledge sharing.

We know that climate change is real - and the disruptions it is causing require us to take action to ensure fish, wildlife, water, land, and people in our region can adapt and build more resilient communities. It was exciting to hear about their important work in this space - and to discuss how I'm working to secure federal investments to support the science and research needed to help directly address many of the climate-related challenges unique to the Pacific Northwest.

name: Donald Norcross
content:
We must do everything in our power to address the recent rise in anti-Semitic violence, which is why I joined more than 130 Democrats & Republicans in urging President Joe Biden to combat antisemitism at home & abroad.

Hate has no place here.

Congressman Ted Deutch
May 28 at 4:03 PM ¬∑

Today I led 133 Democrats and Republicans ‚Äì including progressives and conservatives, from all corners of the country ‚Äì on a bipartisan letter to President Biden urging him to use all available tools to protect the American Jewish community from the rise in antisemitism in our country.

Read the letter below. Thank you to these groups for their support: American Jewish Committee, Anti-Defamation League, Jewish Federations of North America, Hadassah: the Women's Zionist Organization of America, Union of Orthodox Jewish Congregations of America, J Street.

Over the last few weeks, antisemitic incidents have risen by 80 percent in the United States. The American Jewish community has suffered violent physical altercations in cities from Los Angeles to New York; vandalism of synagogues in Tucson and Skokie; and countless attacks on social media platforms, including horrific posts suggesting Jews should return to the gas chambers where millions perished during the Holocaust.

Just days ago, President Biden signed into law the COVID-19 Hate Crimes Act, which included the Jabara-Heyer NO HATE Act, to strengthen our national response to hate crimes after a frightening surge in violence against the Asian American and Pacific Islander community. As we now face a dramatic spike in violent antisemitism across this country, we are urging him to protect the American Jewish community using these new tools and all others at his disposal.

June 1 marks the beginning of hurricane season, and with NOAA predicting another above-normal season, it‚Äôs never too early to prepare. Keep your family safe by reviewing your emergency plans, storm evacuation zones, and preparing hurricane supply kits.

To find hurricane preparation resources such as emergency numbers, hurricane shelters, and more, please visit https://teddeutch.house.gov/constituentservices/hurricanes.htm

The Biden administration is providing $1 billion through FEMA to build disaster-resilient infrastructure, with most of the money going towards disadvantaged communities. President Biden has also signed executive actions such as creating more comprehensive climate and resilience plans across agencies, reinstating the Federal Flood Risk Management Standard to improve resiliency from flooding, and tracking the indicators of climate change at the EPA. These critical actions will help Florida and other states be more prepared for the effects of climate change both in the present and the future.

I encourage everyone to take the necessary precautions in advance to ensure your family‚Äôs safety. Stay safe!

name: Garret Graves
content:
News on Louisiana's Disaster Declaration and helpful links:

Thank you to POTUS for approving a disaster declaration today for Louisiana. We will continue to push for Assumption, Lafourche, Livingston and St. Charles parishes to receive assistance. This severe rainstorm and flooding exacerbated the strain already placed on our communities as we still recover from the pandemic, the freeze earlier this year, and the 2020 hurricane season. I hope President Biden and the respective federal agencies give weight to the compounding effects of these recent disasters that have fatigued local recovery resources and disaster survivors alike. We will continue working with state, local and federal officials to make sure that victims ‚Äì no matter the parish ‚Äì have the opportunity to fully recover.

The President‚Äôs action makes federal funding available to affected individuals in the parishes of Ascension, Calcasieu, East Baton Rouge, Iberville and Lafayette.

We called upon the president to issue a presidential disaster declaration on May 25, 2021 for the Capital Region, Southwest Louisiana and additional parishes in South Louisiana. We will continue to urge for assistance for other parishes including Assumption, Lafourche, Livingston and St. Charles parishes.

The disaster assistance covers damages incurred May 17 ‚Äì 21, 2021 from the severe weather. Assistance can include grants for temporary housing and home repairs, low-cost loans to cover uninsured property losses, and other programs to help individuals and business owners recover from the effects of the disaster.

Residents and business owners who sustained losses in the designated parishes can begin applying for assistance by registering online at http://www.DisasterAssistance.gov or by calling 1-800-621-FEMA(3362) or 1-800-462-7585 (TTY) for the hearing and speech impaired. The toll-free telephone numbers will operate from 7:00 a.m. to 9:00 p.m. (local time) seven days a week until further notice.

We encourage impacted constituents to reach out to one of the Louisiana 6th Congressional District Offices nearby if in need of assistance. Locations and contact information can be found here:
https://garretgraves.house.gov/contact/offices

name: Daniel Webster
content:
Last week, the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs announced the addition of presumptive conditions associated with Agent Orange and other toxic exposures.

As outlined in the bipartisan 2021 NDAA passed by Congress, the VA will add three conditions; bladder cancer, hypothyroidism, and Parkinson's-like symptoms to the list of those presumed to be associated with exposure to toxic chemicals like Agent Orange.

As a result, the VA is working to adjudicate claims and automatically review cases previously filed that were initially denied benefits. If you are a veteran in need of assistance in filing a claim, please contact my office at 352-241-9220.

name: U.S. Helsinki Commission
content:
The Commission on Security and Cooperation in Europe (also known as the Helsinki Commission)‚Äîwas the brainchild of the courageous and tenacious Rep. Millicent Fenwick.

Rep. Fenwick‚Äôs activism was prompted by a 1975 visit to Russia, one week after the Helsinki Final Act was signed. As noted in Amy Shapiro‚Äôs book, ‚ÄúMillicent Fenwick: Her Way,‚Äù the visit brought on a revelation.

‚ÄúYou read about an automobile accident and you‚Äôre shocked,‚Äù Rep. Fenwick said. ‚ÄúBut you come upon that accident and see the blood on the victims and hear their cries ‚Äì how different it is. Well, that‚Äôs what it was like to go to Russia and hear the cries of all these desperate people.‚Äù

Witnessing such devastation first-hand, Rep. Fenwick leapt into action, becoming one of the two primary advocates for the creation of a U.S. body to observe and promote compliance with the human rights provisions of the Helsinki Final Act, alongside Sen. Clifford Case.

Rep. Fenwick became an original member of the Helsinki Commission and served as a commissioner until she retired from Congress.

Walter Cronkite called her ‚Äúthe conscience of Congress.‚Äù She remained a strong opponent of corruption and a driving advocate for human and civil rights throughout her lifetime.

#HelsinkiComm45

name: House Budget Committee
content:
For too long, wealthy tax dodgers have exploited loopholes in our tax code, creating two tax systems:

1Ô∏è‚É£A tax system for hard-working Americans
2Ô∏è‚É£And another for the rich & powerful

But this is our moment to restore fairness and accountability. As five former IRS commissioners wrote in a recent Washington Post op-ed, President Joe Biden‚Äôs tax enforcement proposal will take a significant step toward creating a fairer tax system:

‚ÄúThe significant revenue at stake is a byproduct of the magnitude of the tax gap, which costs the country and honest taxpayers 3 percent of gross domestic product annually in taxes that are owed but unpaid. Uncollected taxes today equal the total taxes paid by the lower 90 percent of individual taxpayers. The scope of the tax compliance problem means that comprehensive proposals to address it would reap substantial benefits.‚Äù

Read our full report on the importance of increasing IRS funding ‚û°Ô∏è https://budget.house.gov/publications/report/funding-irs
